<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,1148,1174]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Description.</emphasis>
Pale yellow with black pattern on head, pro-, and mesonotum (
<figureCitation box="[1014,1153,1148,1175]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–47" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1997,2021]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,535,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-133@11.[174,1412,525,1974]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 29–47. Macropsis spp., lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404167" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404167/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Figs. 36–37</figureCitation>
). Forewings more or less infumose with dark veins. Male darker than female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
Abdominal apodemes of 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[501,517,1220,1234]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
tergite in male wide, rounded, separated by very narrow notch (
<figureCitation box="[1257,1425,1220,1246]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Figs. 190–191</figureCitation>
). Sternal apodemes narrow triangular, separated by U-shaped notch (
<figureCitation box="[906,1005,1256,1282]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Fig. 192</figureCitation>
). Penis stem in side view narrow, usually, bent at almost right angle (
<figureCitation box="[506,672,1292,1318]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Figs. 193–194</figureCitation>
). 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[705,721,1292,1306]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
valvulae of ovipositor very wide, with one preapical tooth each (
<figureCitation box="[160,258,1328,1355]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Fig. 195</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" box="[199,1105,1364,1391]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
Small species; body length (including tegmina): 
<specimenCount box="[744,767,1365,1391]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity box="[779,917,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="3.2" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" unit="mm" value="3.3" valueMax="3.4" valueMin="3.2">3.2–3.4 mm</quantity>
; 
<specimenCount box="[928,949,1365,1391]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity box="[963,1101,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.65" metricValueMax="3.9" metricValueMin="3.4" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" unit="mm" value="3.65" valueMax="3.9" valueMin="3.4">3.4–3.9 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,1400,1426]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Host.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[270,509,1400,1426]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Spiraea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hypericifolia">
<emphasis box="[270,509,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Spiraea hypericifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in European 
<collectingCountry box="[662,739,1400,1426]" name="Russia" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Russia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[752,886,1400,1426]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, and Central Asia, 
<taxonomicName box="[1102,1274,1400,1426]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Spiraea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aquilegifolia">
<emphasis box="[1102,1274,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">S. aquilegifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and, possibly, some other 
<taxonomicName box="[282,369,1436,1462]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Spiraea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[282,369,1436,1462]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Spiraea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in Transbaikalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1472,1498]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Distribution.</emphasis>
Steppe zone of Palearctic from European 
<collectingCountry box="[857,932,1472,1498]" name="Russia" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Russia</collectingCountry>
to Eastern Transbaikalia and 
<collectingCountry box="[1286,1399,1472,1498]" name="Mongolia" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
. In Southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[303,434,1508,1534]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
is common in steppes in the plains and low mountains; the only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lewis" authorityYear="1836" box="[1160,1277,1509,1534]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1160,1277,1509,1534]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Macropsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species abundant outside river valleys.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="393" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1148,1643]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,1580,1606]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Remark.</emphasis>
Identification of this species is based on investigation of 
<typeStatus box="[962,1010,1581,1607]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">type</typeStatus>
specimens from Troitskosavsk (presently Kyakhta Town), Southern Transbaikalia, deposited in ZIN.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1688,1966]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
Species feeding on 
<taxonomicName box="[381,437,1689,1714]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rosa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[381,437,1689,1714]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Rosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[498,765,1688,1714]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Elaeagnaceae" genus="Hippophae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rhamnoides">
<emphasis box="[498,765,1688,1714]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Hippophae rhamnoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are indistinguishable in the shape of the male abdominal apodemes and genitalia and in most cases are also similar in the shape the 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[987,1003,1724,1738]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
valvulae of the ovipositor. At the same time, they distinctly differ from each other in coloration and can be easily identified by external appearance. For this reason, we give a description of apodemes and genitalia here and omit this section in the descriptions of species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1688,1966]" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">
Abdominal apodemes of 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[500,516,1832,1846]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
tergite in male wide, rounded, separated by wide round notch, sternal apodemes narrow triangular, separated by U-shaped angular notch. Penis in side view narrow (
<figureCitation box="[1094,1260,1868,1895]" captionStart="FIGURES 165–203" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[207,1381,183,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-16@21.[205,1382,181,1843]" captionText="FIGURES 165–203. Macropsis aselae sp. n. (165–182), M. illota (183–189), M. sibirica (190–195), M. megerlei (196), M. emeljanovi (197), M. elaeagni (198–199), and M. scabrosa (200–203). 165–167, 183–184, 190–191, 198, 201―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 168–171, 185–186, 192, 199, 202—the 2nd sternite; 172–174, 187–188, 193–194, 196–197, 200―penis, lateral view; 175–177―pygofer process, lateral view; 178–179―style; 180–182, 189, 195, 203―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457948/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">Figs. 196–197</figureCitation>
), bent at almost right angle. 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[298,314,1904,1918]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">nd</superScript>
valvulae of ovipositor with 4–8 preapical teeth each, only in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Horvath, 1904)" baseAuthorityName="Horvath" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[994,1304,1904,1930]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pictipes">
<emphasis box="[994,1118,1905,1930]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="393">M. pictipes</emphasis>
(Horvath, 1904)
</taxonomicName>
with 10–13 preapical teeth each.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
